  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "The cyclical phases price moves through: Expansion (large directional move with shallow pullbacks, often forming FVGs), Retracement (slow shallow pullback against the trend, often into FVG/OB), Consolidation (range-bound oscillation), and Reversal (expansion met with opposing expansion). These phases repeat fractally across time frames.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Expansion: price rapidly breaks prior swing high/low with large-bodied candles closing beyond prior candle ranges, small wicks, shallow opposing pullbacks, often forming FVGs.",
    "Retracement: slow shallow pullback against expansion, failing to close outside prior candle ranges, often touching FVG/OB, forming failure swings on the opposing side.",
    "Consolidation: price oscillates between a defined high and low without closing beyond either extreme, small candle bodies, no directional expansion.",
    "Reversal: expansion is immediately met with opposing expansion, confirmed by change in state of delivery (closing back through opposing candles) or SMT divergence at a point of interest.",
    "Phase transitions confirmed by candle 2 or 3 closure on working time frame and change in state of delivery on lower time frame.",
    "After three or more consecutive expansion candles delivering into liquidity, anticipate phase transition to consolidation or reversal.",
    "Within consolidation, wait for sweep of range high/low before entering; sweep followed by aggressive opposing expansion signals reversal.",
    "Distinguish retracement from reversal: counter-move aggressive (expansion-like) = reversal; slow/shallow = retracement.",
    "Apply fractally across all time frames; anchor transitions to new candle opens on higher time frames.",
    "Expansion respects equilibrium (0.5) on its side; failure to do so flips bias."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Identify current phase to determine entry strategy and bias. In Expansion, favor continuation from shallow retracements into PD arrays; avoid fading active expansion. After multiple expansion candles into liquidity, wait for new phase. In Consolidation, wait for sweep of range high/low before entering. Confirmed Reversals via change in state of delivery allow positioning for new trend. Apply fractally across time frames, aligned with higher time frame bias.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Confusing retracement with reversal: retracement is slow/shallow, reversal is aggressive opposing expansion.",
    "Confusing consolidation with retracement: consolidation is sideways, retracement is directional pullback.",
    "Expecting deep retracements during expansion phase instead of shallow pullbacks.",
    "Entering immediately after large expansion candle without waiting for new phase.",
    "Acting on reversal-looking candle without waiting for candle 2 closure or change in state of delivery.",
    "Trading against in-progress expansion candle instead of waiting for close.",
    "Looking for entries inside consolidation rather than waiting for sweep of range extreme.",
    "Continuing to trade expansion direction after three or more consecutive expansion candles into liquidity.",
    "Trading phase transitions without aligning to higher time frame bias.",
    "Trading reversals off irrelevant swing points before relevant extreme is swept.",
    "Failing to adjust protected swing when reversal signs appear.",
    "Not waiting for enough candle closures to confirm phase transition.",
    "Ignoring equilibrium respect in expansion; using it as bias flip trigger.",
    "Not cross-validating with related assets (SMT divergence)."
  ],
